Hint
You are given an integer array nums of length n.

A trionic subarray is a contiguous subarray nums[l...r] (with 0 <= l < r < n) for which there exist indices l < p < q < r such that:

nums[l...p] is strictly increasing,
nums[p...q] is strictly decreasing,
nums[q...r] is strictly increasing.
Return the maximum sum of any trionic subarray in nums.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [0,-2,-1,-3,0,2,-1]

Output: -4

Explanation:

Pick l = 1, p = 2, q = 3, r = 5:

nums[l...p] = nums[1...2] = [-2, -1] is strictly increasing (-2 < -1).
nums[p...q] = nums[2...3] = [-1, -3] is strictly decreasing (-1 > -3)
nums[q...r] = nums[3...5] = [-3, 0, 2] is strictly increasing (-3 < 0 < 2).
Sum = (-2) + (-1) + (-3) + 0 + 2 = -4.
Example 2:

Input: nums = [1,4,2,7]

Output: 14

Explanation:

Pick l = 0, p = 1, q = 2, r = 3:

nums[l...p] = nums[0...1] = [1, 4] is strictly increasing (1 < 4).
nums[p...q] = nums[1...2] = [4, 2] is strictly decreasing (4 > 2).
nums[q...r] = nums[2...3] = [2, 7] is strictly increasing (2 < 7).
Sum = 1 + 4 + 2 + 7 = 14.
 

Constraints:

4 <= n = nums.length <= 105
-109 <= nums[i] <= 109
It is guaranteed that at least one trionic subarray exists.

// Approach: This problem asks us to find the maximum sum of a "rollercoaster" shaped subarray: it goes up, then down, then up again.This is a classic Dynamic Programming (State Machine) problem. Instead of trying to manage indices l, p, q, r directly (which would be too slow, $O(N^4)$ or $O(N^3)$), we iterate through the array once ($O(N)$) and track the "best possible sum" for each stage of the shape ending at the current index.The Three States (DP Arrays)We maintain three arrays (or variables) as we walk through nums[i]:inc[i] (Increasing): The maximum sum of a strictly increasing subarray ending at index i.dec[i]
// (Up $\to$ Down): The maximum sum of a subarray that has gone up and then down, ending at index i.tri[i] (Up $\to$ Down $\to$ Up): The maximum sum of a full Trionic subarray (Up-Down-Up) ending at index i.Step-by-Step Transition LogicFor each number nums[i], we decide how it extends or starts these sequences.1. State 1: Strictly Increasing (inc)This is standard Kadane's algorithm logic, but restricted to increasing slopes.Condition: If nums[i] > nums[i-1], we can extend the previous increasing sequence.Logic: inc[i] = nums[i] + max(0, inc[i-1]). If the previous sum was negative, we restart the sequence at nums[i].2. State 2: Up $\to$ Down (dec)To be in this state, we must be on a downward slope (nums[i] < nums[i-1]). We can arrive here in two ways:Extend: We were already going down. We just add nums[i] to the previous dec[i-1].Transition (The Peak): We were going up until i-1, and now we drop to i. This makes i-1 the Peak ($p$).Constraint Check: The problem says l < p. This means the increasing part must have at least 2 elements. We check if nums[i-1] > nums[i-2]. If valid, we take the sum of that increasing part plus the current drop.3. State 3: Trionic / Up $\to$ Down $\to$ Up (tri)To be in this state, we must be on an upward slope (nums[i] > nums[i-1]). We can arrive here in two ways:Extend: We were already in the final increasing phase. Add nums[i] to tri[i-1].Transition (The Valley): We were going down until i-1, and now we rise to i. This makes i-1 the Valley ($q$).Constraint Check: The problem says p < q. This means the decreasing part must have at least 2 elements. If dec[i-1] exists (valid state), we simply transition by adding nums[i] to it.

// | Aspect     | Peak Element (162) | Trionic Array II (3640)   |
// | ---------- | ------------------ | ------------------------- |
// | Pattern    | Single peak        | Up → Down → Up            |
// | Scope      | Whole array        | Any subarray              |
// | Output     | Index              | Maximum sum               |
// | Strategy   | Binary search      | DP + prefix logic         |
// | Difficulty | Medium             | Hard                      |
// | Core idea  | Follow slope       | Track structured segments |


#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <climits>

using namespace std;

class Solution {
public:
    long long maxSumTrionic(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        
        // Use a safe "infinity" value within standard limits (10^15)
        const long long INF = 1e15;
        
        vector<long long> inc(n, -INF);
        vector<long long> dec(n, -INF);
        vector<long long> tri(n, -INF);
        
        inc[0] = nums[0];
        
        long long max_sum = -INF;
        
        for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
            // --- 1. Strictly Increasing (inc) ---
            if (nums[i] > nums[i-1]) {
                inc[i] = nums[i] + max(0LL, inc[i-1]);
            } else {
                inc[i] = nums[i];
            }
            
            // --- 2. Up -> Down (dec) ---
            if (nums[i] < nums[i-1]) {
                // Option A: Extend existing dec sequence
                if (dec[i-1] != -INF) {
                    dec[i] = dec[i-1] + nums[i];
                }
                
                // Option B: Transition from inc (Peak was at i-1)
                // Constraint: Increasing part must have length >= 2 => nums[i-1] > nums[i-2]
                if (i >= 2 && nums[i-1] > nums[i-2]) {
                    // We need the sum of the increasing part ending at i-1.
                    // If inc[i-2] > 0, then inc[i-1] is (inc[i-2] + nums[i-1]), which is length >= 2.
                    // If inc[i-2] <= 0, then inc[i-1] is just nums[i-1] (length 1), which is invalid for l < p.
                    // In that invalid case, we must force the pair [nums[i-2], nums[i-1]].
                    long long peakSum;
                    if (inc[i-2] > 0) {
                        peakSum = inc[i-1];
                    } else {
                        peakSum = (long long)nums[i-2] + nums[i-1];
                    }
                    
                    dec[i] = max(dec[i], peakSum + nums[i]);
                }
            }
            
            // --- 3. Up -> Down -> Up (tri) ---
            if (nums[i] > nums[i-1]) {
                // Option A: Extend existing tri sequence
                if (tri[i-1] != -INF) {
                    tri[i] = tri[i-1] + nums[i];
                }
                
                // Option B: Transition from dec (Valley was at i-1)
                // dec[i-1] represents a valid Up->Down sequence ending at i-1.
                // Since dec[i-1] exists, the constraints l < p < q (where q = i-1) are already satisfied.
                // We simply add nums[i].
                if (dec[i-1] != -INF) {
                    tri[i] = max(tri[i], dec[i-1] + nums[i]);
                }
            }
            
            // Update global max
            if (tri[i] != -INF) {
                max_sum = max(max_sum, tri[i]);
            }
        }
        
        return max_sum;
    }
};
